com.ibm.team.repository.common

Interface IExtensibleItem

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IItem, IItemHandle
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    IContributorDetails, IReportDescriptor

    public interface IExtensibleItem
extends IItem

    IExtensibleItem defines methods available on items that allow it's state to be augmented with additional data, referred to as extensions. This is indicated by the model annotation teamClass->allowsStateExtensions (default is false). When a component "opts-in" to extensibility for an item type, they should add this interface to the hierarchy of the facade class for their item (e.g., IWorkItem extends IExtensibleItem).

    The data types permitted for extensions are a subset of the data types allowed for "built-in" modeled attributes. Separate getters and setters exist for each supported extension type.

    Design notes: Fetching a complete (extensible) item will fetch all it's state extensions. When fetching a partial item and state extensions are desired, specify the property ALL_STATE_EXTENSIONS_PROPERTY. Currently for partial item fetches, state extensions are all or nothing; we will be adding API in the future to fetch partial items with a subset of extensions. For any key, only one value may exist as a state extension. It is not legal to have extensions with the same key and different value types.

    The component that declares the item type controls whether its item states can be augmented with extensions. If a component chooses to permit extensions of its item type, it controls the extension keys that are allowed, and their corresponding types. It does this in virtue of providing the only (service) methods that can create and update items of that type, in which it is free to lay down (and enforce) whatever restrictions it chooses.

    Here are some important design considerations to think about when deciding whether to allow state extensions on an item type:

    • Extensions persist until explicitly deleted. Once anyone saves a state of an item X with an extension with key K and value V, then all subsequent states of X will also have the extension K=V. This situation won't change until someone explicitly retrieves X, creates a working copy, deletes the extension for key K, and saves the working copy back as a new state of X.
    • A single item state can carry any number of extensions. The footprint of an item state's extensions (in memory, in the repository, on the wire) grows roughly linearly with the number of extensions.
    • When a complete item is retrieved, the keys and values of all its extensions are automatically included, even if the party doing the retrieving is uninterested/unaware of these extensions.
    • In order to access any of an item's extensions, it is necessary to retrieve the keys and values of all of the item state's extensions.
    Because of these considerations, state extensions should be used carefully and sparingly. If a component writer decides to support state extension for its item type, they should restrict the mechanism so that it is does not become a serious problem at some point.

    • Method Detail

      • getStringExtension

        java.lang.String getStringExtension(java.lang.String key)
        Returns the String value of the extension on this item state for the given key, or null if the item state has no string extension with the given key.

        Use setStringExtension(String, String) on an item working copy to add or update string extensions. Use unsetStringExtension(String) to completely remove the extension key/value pair from the item.

        A return value of null implies one of the following:

        • The item does not have a state extension with that key
        • The item has a state extension with that key, with a value of null. This can be checked using isStringExtensionSet(String)
        Parameters:
        key - the state extension key to be used for accessing and storing the state extension value; must be a qualified name starting with the component id identifying which component is responsible for the given state extension; must not be null or an empty string
        Returns:
        the value of this state extension, which may be null, or null if this item state doesn't have a state extension with the given key
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - if the item type does not support state extensions

      • setStringExtension

        void setStringExtension(java.lang.String key,
                      java.lang.String value)
        Sets the String value of the state extension on this item state as identified by the given key. The item state must be a working copy.

        String extensions are defined as SMALL strings, and thus the size of the values is bounded by IItem.MAX_SMALL_STRING_BYTES. This will be validated when an item working copy is saved.

        When dealing with working copies created from partial item states, specify the ALL_STATE_EXTENSIONS_PROPERTY property when fetching the item state from the repository, to ensure that all of its string extensions are retrieved. If this is not done, you cannot add, update, or remove state extensions of type String on the working copy based on that item state.

        Parameters:
        key - the state extension key to be used for accessing and storing the state extension value; must be a qualified name starting with by the component id identifying which component is responsible for the given state extension; must not be null or the empty string
        value - the value of the state extension, bounded by IItem.MAX_SMALL_STRING_BYTES; null is allowed
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - if the item type does not support state extensions
        See Also:
        IItemType.allowsStateExtensions(), unsetStringExtension(String)

        void setMediumStringExtension(java.lang.String key,
                            java.lang.String value)
        Sets the medium String value of the state extension on this item state as identified by the given key. The item state must be a working copy.

        Medium String extensions are defined as strings with the dbStringSize annotation set to LARGE, and thus the size of the values is bounded by IItem.MAX_MEDIUM_STRING_BYTES. This will be validated when an item working copy is saved.

        When dealing with working copies created from partial item states, specify the ALL_STATE_EXTENSIONS_PROPERTY property when fetching the item state from the repository, to ensure that all of its medium string extensions are retrieved. If this is not done, you cannot add, update, or remove state extensions of type (medium) String on the working copy based on that item state.

        Parameters:
        key - the state extension key to be used for accessing and storing the state extension value; must be a qualified name starting with by the component id identifying which component is responsible for the given state extension; must not be null or the empty string
        value - the value of the state extension, bounded by IItem.MAX_MEDIUM_STRING_BYTES; null is allowed
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - if the item type does not support state extensions
        See Also:

        key - the state extension key to be used for accessing and storing the state extension value; must be a qualified name starting with by the component id identifying which component is responsible for the given state extension; must not be null or the empty string
        Returns:
        true if the int extension exists on the item; otherwise false
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - if the item type does not support state extensions
